{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8869b499-8ed9-410f-bcba-e8a23d9db7ac","content":"Run **`dotnet workload update`**.\n\nHere's the difference:\n\n| Command | What it does |\n|---|---|\n| `dotnet workload update` | Downloads and installs the **latest versions** of all installed workloads to match your current SDK. |\n| `dotnet workload repair` | **Reinstalls** the same workload versions already recorded — fixes corrupted files but doesn't upgrade anything. |\n\nAfter an SDK update, the installed workload versions often lag behind the new SDK. `workload update` pulls versions that are compatible with your updated SDK. `workload repair` would just re-download the old (now-incompatible) versions.\n\n**Quick fix:**\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\ndotnet build\n```\n\nIf `update` alone doesn't resolve it, also try `dotnet workload restore` in your project directory — it ensures all workloads referenced by your project's `TargetFramework` (e.g., `net8.0-ios`) are installed.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"6abcffe7-f725-44d9-99a5-0e18d356755a","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI workload management — specifically whether to use `dotnet workload update` or `dotnet workload repair` after a .NET SDK update broke their build.\n\nThis is a general knowledge question, not a codebase task. I can answer directly.\n\n- `dotnet workload update` — downloads and installs the latest versions of all installed workloads. This is what you want after an SDK update, because the workload versions need to match the new SDK.\n- `dotnet workload repair` — reinstalls all installed workloads. It doesn't upgrade them; it just re-downloads the same versions to fix corrupted installations.\n\n\n- So for this situation, `dotnet workload update` is the right command to run.","outputTokens":405,"requestId":"9BCD:1FFE72:628DE84:6DB6062:69EC0E24"},"id":"b2d567e4-f12e-49f2-bc44-e21bb0764033","timestamp":"2026-04-25T00:43:27.106Z","parentId":"594917c1-77f9-47f1-a83d-4a94a6fa3bd2"}
